nodes.body: messageFile.md
Is it not true in general that the manifold boundary of a closed set `C : Set ‚Ñù‚Åø` (which is a manifold) is `frontier C`? How much harder would it be to prove that directly?

This is an obvious question. Let's assume we talk about a closed subset of `C : Set R^n` which is the closure of an open set.
(Otherwise, we could be talking about closed submanifolds of R^n... for which this is harder (and mathlib currently doesn't know about submanifolds).)

The mathlib definition is "a point is a boundary point if it is mapped to the frontier via its preferred chart" (i.e., `extChartAt H x x` lies in `frontier (range (extChartAt H x))`). Since closed intervals are defined using two charts, a priori you have to do *some* work to deal with this --- which is what this PR does.

Mathematically, you can say "but 0 lies in the frontier under the obvious identity chart to R".
Formalising this requires the innocuous-looking lemma "if x is a boundary point is independent of the choice of chart".
This lemma has a simple proof for 1-manifolds and a harder proof for 2-manifolds (using the fundamental group of spheres; not sure if mathlib has these already). In general, proving this requires invariance of domain (which uses* e.g. the homology groups of spheres: these have been formalised in Lean 3, but re-doing this in mathlib would take significant time: see zulip for Brouwer's fixed point theorem).
(For smooth manifolds, the general case follows from the inverse function theorem. Yet, long-term that's not a proof I'd like to see in mathlib, as the result also holds in the topological category.)

<details>
<summary>* small detour</summary>

There are proofs of Brouwer/invariance of domain without using algebraic topology, but e.g. Sperner's lemma instead. (See e.g. [Tao's blog](https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2011/06/13/brouwers-fixed-point-and-invariance-of-domain-theorems-and-hilberts-fifth-problem/) or [this stackexchange answer](https://math.stackexchange.com/a/2316534) for some references. Sperner himself proved invariance of domain, for example. I would prefer not to spend my time on this. Homology groups of spheres are extremely basic algebraic topology; mathlib will need them eventually.)

</details>

**Short version**: I don't think you'd get a shorter proof.
I could add a lemma "being interior is independent of the chosen chart" just for dimension 1, with a TODO to generalise the proof. The proof would not be re-usable; I'm not sure if this would be useful. (In practice, everything you need to know about 1-manifolds and their boundary is in this PR: you don't gain anything from the generality.)
I was expecting that the answer would be "no", but I didn't think homology of spheres would enter the picture üòÑ Fine by me to leave the result as is
